Certainly! To successfully integrate a "Go" snippet that generates a list of numbers from 1 to 10 and checks if each number is even or odd, you can use the following code snippet:

```go
package main

import "fmt"

func main() {
    for i := 1; i <= 10; i++ {
        if i%2 == 0 {
            fmt.Printf("%d is even\n", i)
        } else {
            fmt.Printf("%d is odd\n", i)
        }
    }
}
```

This Go code snippet is a simple loop from 1 to 10. It uses the modulus operator `%` to determine if a number is even (i.e., divisible by 2 with no remainder). If the condition `i%2 == 0` is true, it prints that the number is even; otherwise, it prints that the number is odd. This example demonstrates basic control flow and arithmetic operations in Go. To run this program, simply copy it into a file with a .go extension, for example, `evenOdd.go`, and run it using the Go command `go run evenOdd.go` in your terminal or command prompt.

Certainly! Below is a Kotlin snippet that demonstrates how to create a simple function to check if a number is prime. This function takes an integer as input and returns a boolean indicating whether the number is prime or not.

```kotlin
fun isPrime(num: Int): Boolean {
    if (num <= 1) {
        return false
    }
    for (i in 2..Math.sqrt(num.toDouble()).toInt()) {
        if (num % i == 0) {
            return false
        }
    }
    return true
}

fun main() {
    val number = 29
    if (isPrime(number)) {
        println("$number is a prime number.")
    } else {
        println("$number is not a prime number.")
    }
}
```

This code first checks if the number is less than or equal to 1, as numbers less than 2 are not prime by definition. It then uses a loop to check divisibility from 2 up to the square root of the number. If any divisor is found, it returns `false`; otherwise, it returns `true` confirming the number is prime. The `main` function demonstrates the usage of `isPrime` by checking if 29 is a prime number.

