Certainly! Here's a PHP snippet that demonstrates how to connect to a MySQL database using PDO (PHP Data Objects). This code provides a secure way to establish a database connection, handle potential connection errors, and ensures that the database credentials are not hardcoded into the script but are instead retrieved from environment variables.

```php
<?php
// Database configuration settings
$host = getenv('DB_HOST'); // Get the host from environment variable
$dbname = getenv('DB_NAME'); // Get the database name from environment variable
$username = getenv('DB_USER'); // Get the database username from environment variable
$password = getenv('DB_PASS'); // Get the database password from environment variable

// DSN (Data Source Name)
$dsn = "mysql:host=$host;dbname=$dbname";

// PDO options
$options = [
    PDO::ATTR_ERRMODE => PDO::ERRMODE_EXCEPTION,
    PDO::ATTR_DEFAULT_FETCH_MODE => PDO::FETCH_ASSOC,
    PDO::ATTR_EMULATE_PREPARES => false,
];

try {
    // Create a PDO instance (connect to the database)
    $pdo = new PDO($dsn, $username, $password, $options);
    echo 'Connection successful!';
} catch (PDOException $e) {
    // Handle connection errors
    die("Could not connect to the database $dbname :" . $e->getMessage());
}
?>
```

This code snippet ensures that the database connection is secure and handles errors gracefully. Using environment variables for sensitive information like database credentials is a good practice, protecting your database from unauthorized access.

Certainly! If you need to extract all the email addresses from a text file using Perl, you can use the following Perl script. This script reads from a text file and prints all discovered email addresses to the standard output.

```perl
#!/usr/bin/perl
use strict;
use warnings;

# Open the file (provided via command line)
my $filename = $ARGV[0];
open(my $fh, '<', $filename) or die "Could not open file '$filename' $!";

# Regex pattern to find email addresses
my $email_pattern = qr/\b[A-Za-z0-9._%+-]+@[A-Za-z0-9.-]+\.[A-Z]{2,}\b/i;

# Read the file line by line
while (my $line = <$fh>) {
    # Check for matches 
    while ($line =~ /$email_pattern/g) {
        print "$&\n";  # Print each email found
    }
}

# Close the file handle
close($fh);
```

To run this script, save it as `extract_emails.pl`, make sure it's executable, and run it from the command line by providing the filename from which you want to extract email addresses, like so:
```bash
perl extract_emails.pl inputfile.txt
```
This script operates by opening the specified file, iterating through each line of the file, and using a regular expression to find patterns that match email addresses. Each found email address is printed. Adjust the regular expression if you have specific needs regarding the email format.

